Poland and cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of that agency, the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before the second world war, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always find understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his work of avant-garde entitled "Introduction to Astronautics ".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in the Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a world-renowned spacecraft propagator, his contribution has been rewarded in particular by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket was to be used to propulse or stop the drain.
The only known information about this drain is that of the press of the day.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It is evident from the documents preserved that this research had reached the stage of the tests.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photo-hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
The purpose of these two projects was military use of rocket engines.
Just prior to the war, all the plans to use the rocket technique were carried out by the interim scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Comitéet Doradczo-Nukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to the aircraft were published in the Polish press, thanks to Polish astronaut society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of the Problem Journal, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to the aircraft.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Mr. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to the astronauts
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautics Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautics Federation (created in 1951) and from the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, PTA's first president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautics Federation.
He kept his job until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first was launched on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version was built, RM-1A, and during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have ranged up to 14.5 km and served to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket was developed during the period 1962 - 1965, followed by the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of devices was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
The repeal of the law on public utility is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on public utility.
This decision has raised in public opinion a lively discussion.
It is certainly interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means in practice that the various economic entities and national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital linked to a frenzied financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) generate tension over prices.
This means that a producer strives to import goods sold at low prices to resist economic competition by "making the price of the competitor more expensive" in order to remove a larger share of the market and thereby increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad or buying at low prices or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Given that private capital has no social responsibility and hence responsibility vis-à-vis the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the State are necessarily increasing.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of employers to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for the benefit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital generate in the various economies a situation in which governments of different countries are forced to engage in a mutual competition to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital.
In other words, governments place their own population at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the private capital price dictatorship, particularly in the area of wages.
This occurs on the one hand through a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment, and on the other, by restricting the rights of employees in the field of labour law.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the RFA, there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot meet their needs with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
As a result of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is forced to pay a supplement so that they reach the vital minimum.
Such a scandal, for example, has been updated in the case of employees working as an auxiliary to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the Member States of the south of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under pressure from a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to live with wages of poverty, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital would invest in their country.
Here we have to ask ourselves the following question: where does this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also concerns all Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the State cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even today, does not govern, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same, the entire state.
The answer to this question is no doubt true.
The evidence is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby in all States.
As a result, there is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In the FFR, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, national departments delegate the development of bills to law firms closely related to industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as declared by Western-type constitutions, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that democracies oriented towards liberalism are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "the crisis of the Roman Empire in the time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State was long in full delicacy and the functions were attributed to violence.
The beatings of wine pots, the favors obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The sub-de-tables and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with voices already sold" ... ... "The honest people were not looking for any functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls" ... "It was really started to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man" ... It is true that Appianos had in mind Pomped, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into absoluteist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, with no regard for the interests of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
Today, as in the past, it results in a decline without prior elites, without any effort to carry out reforms in depth.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalisation of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems for liberal-type democracies can be seen as a sort of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss in human life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today, as well as crimes against humanity as we know them from past and recent history.
