The Argo movie: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters composed of Islamic students attacked the American Embassy of Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. administration a positive outcome; it could not, in fact, abandon Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the liberation of hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, which was further aggravated by the fiasco's attempt to free hostages by force.
The diplomats arrested were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations by the Algerian Government.
Their fate brings about a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed strongly to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory to America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated periods, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team to make screenings for a major science-fiction film.
Gender combination
Tony Mendez's plan of exfiltration requires Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation were long kept secret, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is on the one hand a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, a betrayal - such as in the Ocean's leven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
Ambients follow: sequences of documentary-style Tehran (in the sub-titled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were retranslated into the film, there are no great differences),
The lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, corridors and telephone...
Ben Affleck managed to reboot his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected stagewriter and his acting game ceased to generate ironic remarks.
Argo is his third long film after the dark cop "Gone Baby Gone " (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in its original city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the false shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The stage director had to be content with a subject offering in fact only a few palpitating scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It is very good, it sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is removed by a phone shot in America and the continuation on the landing track is quite drawn by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events to too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operatives, their characters would have earned a greater place and are not, far from there, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks some dramatic tension, it is seen with moderate interest, appreciating the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
He drives the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of yet another story, in a certain way, incomplete to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the business.
