The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual public investigation of the most absurd banking costs, has now decided to launch the competition of the regulation or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU is now considering adopting a 40 percent quota of women for the management of large European companies was at the root of our decision," said the organizer of this survey, Patrik Nacher, for the Právo newspaper.
Among the absurdities mentioned, for example, there is already a recent decision by the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
To date, however, women were advantaged with life insurance rates because they are objectively a lower risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other idea as incredible as "the EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013," said Nacher.
The EU’s controversial regulations include, for example, the obligation to add bio-components to fuels, which have adverse environmental consequences, or the prohibition on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively low quantity of a dangerous substance or the directive on the size of chicken cages, leading to increased egg prices.
Critics have also been issued in the past against the fact ban to use the term "butre à tartiner" or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional bulbs.
Quality bananas must have a size of 14 cm.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose applications are usually defended in Brussels by a State or a group of States (also the Czech Republic currently imposes claims on its banks by threatening to use its veto).
The interests of the pressure groups are also, for example, the origin of the fact that bananas in the Union must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curve".
The European Commission argued that it was merely harmonising non-homogenous national standards that complicated trade.
The rules on fruit and vegetables have been softened despite the opposition of some States, claiming that existing directives lead to waste of food.
The first price may be awarded in this investigation in the EU regulation of last year that must include a warning on inflatable balloons that children under the age of 8 must not swell without adult supervision.
The EU referred to an US survey that balloons are among toys the first cause of child death by suffocation.
A similar restriction applies to children under 14 years of age in the case of blowing in fair bells.
We also have strange ideas.
The following rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this theme for Greece, anyone with an official role within the EU cannot use the name "Macedoine" and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the "Let Do" association of liberal economists, the Bankovnipoplatky.com server has appointed in this investigation, in addition to certain absurdities mentioned above, the Union Regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food reserves that could be found on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then goes beyond, for example, the fixed volumes for canned mushrooms and thus risks a heavy fine.
The organizers of this investigation found it interesting to pay money to some countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a grant to apply for grants.
These ideas, however, are not from Brussels but from Prague.
"The fact that we don't have a sea handicaps us.
