Stefan Spermon, a computerist in a large neighbouring company, tells us, "Yes, it's really nice, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, iPad and e-books.
Today, no one is going on his own free will in one of these bookstores, right?
Spijkenisse, a Dortoir town that has nothing attractive to the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls shows the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get back on the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from Rotterdam MVRDV's architects' office, master of audacious stick diagrams and creator of buildings full of mind and often cynical, accepted the project with its usual flegme and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a line on the face.
And while the members of the jury were still watching, disconcerting and waving their shoulders, Maas, confronted him, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and finished his speech with activist arguments by a: "common cry!"
Here it is, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, or as it is said, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million-euro mountain has flown from land.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and some semi-detached buildings and houses for a total of 50 houses.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
This is how this small terne village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a mayory of an oarsing laider, whose white facades invite them to think that they shelter a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Of course, a lift takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you soak the floor of the building in the discovery of its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant reverberations speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking at public benches, dogs and small boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Usually, library rays are located along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," explains Willy Maas.
We have completely altered the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books was properly built: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environment centre and the building's technical plant.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes laminates, sometimes balustrades, sometimes climbing ramps.
A new experience for seeing, touching and smelling.
Even the architects and engineers of the endurcis building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in an agricultural company ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, for years, the synthetic membrane of a millimetre of thickness has been used as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The membrane end is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was first compressed in such quantities in plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary coffee offers us an impressive view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pot figs.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute mainly to maintaining the ideal level of air moisture in the literary mountain.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project for ecology," Trouborst says.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only gives light to the interior, even on the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across from the glass façade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated stores take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, described even the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" by Spijkenisse.
