The concept is a success.
The rays are all over the place.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
In this way, MVRDV has achieved the master's discipline, which is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose abstention when voting on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer status in the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think she doesn't support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, however, without being too critical to Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen abstention when voting on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have any difficulty in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to be defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean to the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt independent positions of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
The German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position towards the conflict in the Near East and abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important developments in the Near East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must take care not to undermine public opinion, but also the elites of Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this because it is not a unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic reflections.
Does Germany interfere with its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will not be respected any more.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are varied.
On the other hand, the United States announced their veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and most European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that the true differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem so.
If you observe relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from enthusiastic about Netanyahou's policy.
Is Germany experiencing difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think it's easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
Therefore, they cannot join a broader political line and must assert their unique position.
This is what they are doing in the euro issue at the moment.
In my opinion, Germany will play a locomotive role in the future and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
That has always been a delicate question.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they have to play a role that makes them more independent.
Does Germany play a role as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it still difficult to take on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still faces difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed with neighbors and very varied opinions, and this is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only decreasing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this gap, which is still there?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant and if they're just less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Protection of trademarks" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially deposited in China, but has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys protection such that the company bearing its name cannot complain.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd make a profit.
"It is increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer of the Taylor Wessing firm specializing in violation of the right to property in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my office.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to record their trademarks.
So, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
