Therefore, I had enough time to reflect on the theme of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spend a half-day at an airport waiting for a flight is quite boring, even when you have books, magazines and iPhones to distract you (not forgetting the duty-free shops).
But increasingly, some academics and experts specializing in child development commend the boredom.
It is perfectly normal for us - and our children - to get bored from time to time, they say.
This forces the brain to take interesting paths or even to feed creativity.
And since we are, for the most part, constantly in front of several types of screens, we no longer know the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome the boredom with open arms?
Yes.
And no.
But I'll be back.
First of all, like many people, I thought boredom was a rather recent phenomenon, especially since we had more free time.
But that is not the case, says Peter Toohey, professor of Greek-Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011).
"The bore goes very far," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii are Latin graffiti that evokes boredom, they date back to the first century.
Then there is the definition that we give to boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in various ways, said John D. Eastwood, Associate Professor of Psychology at York University, Ontario, Canada.
After having gone through many publications and submitted the idea to a discussion group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience that consists of " wanting to do something, but not succeeding in engaging in a satisfactory activity."
What distinguishes the boredom of apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task although she would like it.
With apathy, he says, there's no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of boredom, he said, is "the interruption of the attention process, associated with a maussated mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
The boredom can look like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that if both can be linked, people who are bored tend to think that the problem comes from the environment or from the world, while depressed people think that the problem is from them.
Sometimes we may think we're bored when it's actually a concentration problem.
As part of their study, "The Uninvolved Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", which was published in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an older experience in which the participants listened on tape, the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard, from the next room, the too high sound of a TV show that had no report, others just heard the TV show, and the third group did not at all hear the soundtrack.
Those who heard TV at a low sound level said that they were more bored than the other two groups - they had difficulty concentrating, but did not know why, and attributed this problem of concentration to boredom.
When you are trying to focus on a difficult or relevant task, an interruption of attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you do a boring task, "like looking at objects on a assembly chain, music can help you not to get bored."
In fact, he says, now we know that when we are torturing or scruffing, these gestures, often regarded as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to remain physically more alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to stutter learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stay unmoved," said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored one day or another - the delay of my plane flight, a speaker with a single-corded voice, a particularly boring film.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To measure this, researchers developed a "Scale of predisposition to boredom" in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements like, "Among the tasks I do, many of them are repetitive and monotonous," and "I have so many centers of interest that I don't have time to do everything."
Using such a scale, researchers have found that boys tend to become more bored than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, and in particular need of numerous and varied stimulations.
But in general, teenagers are quick to blame.
In 1991, Reed Larson, an individual and community development professor at the University of Illinois, conducted an experience in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
He noted that 32 per cent of adolescents claimed to be bored at school and during their homework at home, while 23 per cent said to be bored when they were not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson stated that he did not know whether today's percentages of boredom, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he added that he knew that "adolescence is a time when boredom reaches its highest level," especially because children and adolescents do not have much control over what they want to do.
If I rest my question: is boredom good for you?
Sometimes not, because in its extreme form, this can lead people to take absurd physical risks, betting or abusing certain substances to spend time, as studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers point to a link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying the problem for more than two decades.
"The boredom is the way the brain has found to let you know that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the N.Y.U.
But the brain does not always know what the most appropriate thing to do.
If you get bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
But if you watch TV, it will make you happy in the short term, but not in the long term.
So if your child gets bored and you give him an iPad, he won't get bored anymore, but he won't learn to take care of himself or self-governing himself, says Professor Fenske.
And "this self-regulation goes from one situation to another," he says.
Your child not only learns to have fun, he gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should glorify boredom.
Just as I don't think we should criticize him either.
Feeling comfortable outside the constant boiling that generates activities and technology is the goal we should tend to achieve.
Professor Eastwood agrees on this.
"We need to get bored more often, but boredom awakens an acute and frenetic desire to be connected to something that makes sense," he said.
According to him, what people are looking for is a way to disconnect and appreciate stopping times.
"In an environment where we are constantly hyperstimulated," he added, "it's hard to find ways to get into something when the noise stops."
