The hardest trade in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the wearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by carrying the breath of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas emanating from the earth's guts solidifies to the contact of the air.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There is only 250 metres to the top of the volcano that reaches 2,386 meters above altitude, but exhausted carriers put more than 40 minutes to scale this distance, at a tortoise, keeping the balance and measuring their steps not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their life, as it happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen's miners earn 5 cents euros for each kilo of extracted sulphur.
Once at the top, he wanders a path among tourists photographing them as if they were circus animals, and carrying heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little in contravention at 1,850 meters high.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents euros) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to 10,000 rupees (83 cents euros) to the petrochemical industry as this mineral is very present in everyday life and is used to manufacture candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 dollars (3,8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who generally travels three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and ends exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 dollars (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such superhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would earn in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (EUR 1,20) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (EUR 167)", says the carrier who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was €75,000 (€6.20) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java for her to convert to Islam."
Then he suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, cough constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At age 27, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulphur has already begun to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Then he suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, cough constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases rejected by the volcano.
It's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work for another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in English more than acceptable.
Despite life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, a server or a receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the work of a mule.
He shares an unhealthy wood measure with other carriers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulphur never ceases to melt at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by lighting up with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs and provides no equipment to carriers who work for them and are paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not touch a sub of the 30,000 rupees (EUR 2,50) of increase per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (EUR 1,20), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is done for animals, not humans," protest Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for 30 years, since he left the college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilos, he ensures that he will not stop working "as long as he can" because he needs money to raise his three sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my life.
Although the sulphur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the minors in the thick smoke columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering serious diseases... to which their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets are added.
