The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the release of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Ef has tried several times to access the document signed at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of States and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency first reported that it would be disclosed after the end of the summit, then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian Government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to summit information has been consistently limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, limited audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information among journalists was given by press officers from some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media demanding more important information.
Later, Peru's presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech rather than the official document that concluded the summit.
In October, Peru was host to the 3rd Arab South American Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was requested with the press, it had not also issued the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was issued last March.
During the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which establishes a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the trial that Lima has tried against Santiago and that starts in The Hague on Monday.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we bring before this international court today," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of international disputes, treaties and tribunals," added President Piñera by handing President Humala a hand, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international court, after a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011, after the removal of its former President Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that 31 project lines had been established among South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
