With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and find a better future for our people," said President Humala.
"We decided to favour a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were concerned with Peru and were on the transverse axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide any further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions Paraguay's political situation.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow it to be re-entered into the South American Union," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday next to Mexico to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through a judgement of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
