Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth (Texas), worldwide became known for the leading role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied a man of business without scruples, fearless and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as an unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who came back this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of cancer complications, according to a family release sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved native town of Dallas, once again playing the ironic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry's family and his close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of her wife in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said his press officer, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all those who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived his life in full," Gray said in a press release.
The doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis in Larry Hagman in 1992 and he had recognized having been drinking for many years.
In 1995, he had been detected with a malignant liver tumor and had been grafted.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television as an ordinary type in the series "Jinny of my dreams" broadcast by the NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also played in two comedies that remained short on the antenna, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles at the cinema are well-received roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterly interpretation of the deliciously disgusting J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The dramatic series of the CBS chain on the Ewing clan and their relatives was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
