A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when Professor of Religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hammock there: the end of the "great discount" of the Maya calendar on 21 December, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax wrench that some called "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of the end of time thought that the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé this week to his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we said it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach on "the end of the world" this semester, which, in theory, will be the last of history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker offers the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas thrive with time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," said Vacker.
On the main campus of the University of State of Pennsylvania, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an Assistant Professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world would not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, which does not leave students of any choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, from the University of Rutgers-Camden.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Nursery, says he has seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, and even less one teacher, told us to believe in the end of the world on December 21.
"Our first project was about Maya prophecy, and in a way we discredited it," says Julie Zegle, a senior student in Temple, aged 21 and from West Chester.
The Mayas never predicted the end of the world, it's just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I agree that there is anxiety related to the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back to several centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has led to an increase in these speculations.
"In other parts of the globe, people don't think about it," he says.
This is mostly the Anglophone world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at the University of La Salle who gave courses to the Philippines this year, responded quickly when he was asked if he knew that we were taking courses here on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines do not participate in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, many of the alleged dates of last judgment have been discussed, and he states that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately begin to think about the next date" or the philosopher that December 21 marks the beginning of a 7-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Several told us they thought they were going to parties "from the end of the world."
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
